would jeopardize the efforts of soviet president mikhail s 
gorbachev to improve relations with the west and reform the soviet 
system 
in warsaw walesa continued to jockey with communist authorities 
over who should lead the government 
walesa said he was willing to serve as prime minister if 
society wants it and polish president wojciech jaruzelski called 
for a joint meeting soon of the countrys major political leaders to 
find a rational solution for the deepening governmental crisis 
in an interview with warsaw radio polish service walesa issued 
an assurance clearly aimed at assuaging kremlin fears saying that 
changes in the polish government would not represent a threat to 
the warsaw pact 
state department spokesman boucher declined to comment directly 
on the pravda article but said us officials note that poland 
faces a difficult period of transition from a state dominated by one 
party to a more pluralistic and democratic system 
this process must be managed within poland itself the 
formation of a new polish government is an internal matter for the 
polish people to decide we hope that a new government will be 
formed as soon as possible he said 
another state department official speaking on condition of 
anonymity described the situation in poland as very delicate 
but said that the soviet warning was not viewed with great alarm in 
washington 
it was not even as strong as a shot across the bow said the 
source 
a third government source also speaking on condition that he not 
be further identified said us officials did not think it likely 
that gorbachev would choose or be forced by conservatives in his 
country to order a crackdown in poland in the near future 
