<TEXT>
iran has begun a crackdown on a lucrative 
trade in smuggling persian rugs to evade strict controls on carpet 
exports 
last month authorities in southern bushehr province seized more 
than 750 silk rugs in what the official islamic republic news agency 
said was the biggest carpet haul so far the agency said the rugs 
were worth millions of dollars 
the rugs were hidden inside tanker trucks and would have been 
illegally shipped from a port on irans persian gulf coast irna 
said the agency was monitored in nicosia 
persian gulf merchants say most smuggled persian rugs are shipped 
across the gulf to the coast of the united arab emirates and trucked 
to warehouses in dubai the regions major trading center 
the crackdown on carpet smuggling from bushehr province started 
in july following similar campaigns against narcotics and arms 
smugglers 
it followed reports in irans staterun media that contraband 
carpet exports would soon outstrip legal sales abroad 
according to official statistics rug exports earned iran at 
least 260 million last year or more than onethird of its nonoil 
exports iranian newspapers estimated another 200 million worth 
were smuggled abroad 
silk rugs which cost five times as much as wool ones account 
for about 15 percent of carpets legally sold abroad 
dubai merchants say a trickle of legal exports provides the cover 
for a huge smuggling network with dealers flying in from japan and 
western europe to pick up bargains in persian carpets 
irans carpet industry used to employ more than 2 million people 
who spent the winter months weaving carpets in their villages 
but production fell sharply following the 1979 islamic revolution 
and the ouster of the monarchy political turmoil shut down major 
exporting firms and villagers from recessionhit weaving districts 
flocked to the cities to seek jobs 
soaring inflation meant that imports of fine wools and dyes 
needed for highquality carpets were sharply reduced it takes 
several years to weave a large carpet in a complex multicolored 
design 
in the revolutions early days carpet exports were banned on the 
grounds they were part of the nations store of wealth 
now customs officers value carpets before they can be shipped 
abroad and exporters have to hand over their foreign currency 
earnings to the government in exchange for iranian rials at an 
artificially low rate 
during the persian gulf war between iran and iraq dealers in the 
syrian capital of damascus stocked up on rugs sold by iranian 
tourists given governmentpaid trips to syria because their 
relatives had died as martyrs fighting iraq syria was irans 
main ally during the eightyear conflict 
the iranians would bring a small silk rug or two to sell in 
syria but after the ceasefire last year there arent nearly so 
many iranians visiting said nazir nahawndi a dealer in damascus 
cavernous hamadiye bazaar 
despite competition from lowerpriced rugs made in india china 
and turkey traditional persian rugs are still appreciated western 
european dealers say 
comparatively speaking persian carpets are selling for the 
equivalent of 1960s prices and they dont wear out unlike the 
new far east rugs firouz selmi an iranian merchant in frankfurt 
said in a telephone interview 
antique rugs some almost 100 years old are an investment that 
rates with anything else on the international art market he added 
a modern rug measuring 6 feet by 6 feet from a leading maker in 
the southern iranian city of isfahan a renowned carpet center can 
sell for upwards of 15000 at a london auction house 
in damascus rug merchants mostly buy from private homes as 
syrian families sell off the family heirlooms and switch to fitted 
carpets prices are considerably lower 
a goodquality shiraz rug measuring 10 feet by 6 feet costs less 
than 1500 a topquality throw rug in varied colors from kashan or 
in deep red with bold dark designs from bokhara costs about 2000 
prices are still reasonable because we get enough stock from 
the old houses but its a limited supply and it cant last that 
much longer said david hamedan whose family runs an antique 
store in the heart of the mazelike damascus bazaar 
</TEXT>
