<TEXT>
housing construction continued to rebound from 
the depressing effects of high mortgage rates with a 08 percent 
increase in new starts last month the government reported today 
this could mean more jobs in the construction and building 
materials industries and additional employment and sales in such 
housingrelated businesses as home furnishings and appliances 
the commerce department reported that new homes and apartments 
were built in july at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 143 
million units up from 142 million units in june when the rebound 
began 
the housing industry had been among the sectors hardest hit 
earlier this year as the federal reserve drove interest rates up to 
restrain economic growth and contain inflation 
construction starts had fallen for four consecutive months 
through may the longest string of declines since activity slowed 
for five months in a row from february through june 1987 the may 
level of 131 million units was the slowest pace since the 13 
million rate in december 1982 
but the central bank began nudging rates down in june and in 
anticipation of that move fixedrate mortgages began falling from 
their peak of 1122 percent in march the federal national mortgage 
association said fixed rates had dropped to 996 percent by last 
friday 
the july construction pace followed a hefty 85 percent hike in 
june the highest since a 86 percent jump to 151 million units in 
february 1988 
but junes increase reflected a 329 percent rise in the volatile 
apartment construction the highest since a 43 percent increase in 
april 1988 apartment construction last month fell 12 percent to an 
annual rate of 389000 units it had increased 54 percent in may 
after falling 266 percent in april 
construction of singlefamily homes in july rose 63 percent to 
an annual rate of 104 million units singlefamily starts had risen 
02 percent in june after falling 51 percent in may and 47 percent 
in april 
analysts had expected singlefamily construction to remain weak 
as the economy continued to slow causing a buildup in unsold new 
homes 
by region overall housing construction jumped by 16 percent last 
month in the northeast where starts rose to a seasonally adjusted 
annual rate of 196000 units 
starts were up 11 percent to 272000 units in the midwest but 
fell 43 percent to 530000 units in the south and 42 percent to 
432000 units in the west 
applications for building permits a barometer of future 
multifamily housing activity were down 31 percent in july 
following a drop of 29 percent in june they had risen 1 percent in 
may and 85 percent in april after three consecutive monthly 
declines 
