<TEXT>
time has erased most of the scars 
left along the mississippi gulf beachfronts by hurricane camille 
but for survivors the horrors of the 1969 killer are as vivid as 
yesterday 
we live with the memory of camille said civil defense 
director wade guice theres another camille out there somewhere 
and i just pray it doesnt come in here 
the most powerful storm in us history camille danced along the 
coast for days before roaring ashore in mississippi the night of 
aug 17 1969 camilles 200 mph winds smashed everything in its 
path and it unleashed a wall of water as high as 30 feet 
two hundred fortyeight people died including 141 in mississippi 
structures that had withstood major hurricanes of the past 
including betsy in 1965 vanished under camilles tidal wave large 
ships were tossed onto dry land with a 200foot barge coming to 
rest across what was left of us 90 at the time the major traffic 
artery along the coast 
i flew down there the next morning and it was incredible 
recalled us rep gv sonny montgomery dmiss i had seen 
total destruction in battle zones in europe and in vietnam but 
nothing like this 
there were no cars no people moving it was very 
frightening he said 
in the weeks following camille national guardsmen patrolled 
streets to prevent looting volunteers from across the country 
arrived to help remove debris and provide food and shelter for 
hundreds of homeless 
losses from the storm which also caused extensive damage along 
coastal louisiana and alabama and spawned scores of tornadoes 
inland was placed at 15 billion with most of the loss coming in 
mississippi guice said 
camille destroyed 6744 homes and damaged 46709 more while 
destroying or damaging 746 businesses 
harbor facilities have been rebuilt and the sand beach reclaimed 
over the years but there are reminders driveways leading to empty 
lots twisted aging trees and even a souvenir shop built next to a 
shrimp boat that rests near where it was blown ashore 
when a hurricane gets in the gulf you see people looking out 
over the mississippi sound wondering if another camille is 
coming said george byrd harbor master at the gulfport small 
craft harbor before that storm people always felt things wouldnt 
be as bad as the weather people were predicting well camille 
changed all that 
the storm left another calling card for shrimpers along the coast 
as receding waters sucked debris back into the gulf 
there were lots of shrimp out here after camille but you 
couldnt drag but about 10 minutes before you would have to pull the 
nets in to clean out the referigerators car batteries pilings and 
things like that said mike sevel who as a 16yearold at the 
time worked with his father aboard their shrimp boat 
we even had zippers on our nets so they could be opened 
quickly to dump the debris 
jacqueline hines and her husband had ridden out hurricanes for 
more than 50 years and saw no reason to abandon their beachfront 
home in gulfport despite the urging of friends and neighbors 
within a few hours the two were clinging for life 30 feet up a 
television antenna watching as gulf waters crushed their home and 
covered the twostory house next door 
how can one forget a night like that asked mrs hines 79 
everything we had things that can never be replaced are gone 
forever 
mrs hines recalls the violent wind that pinned her head back for 
hours the blinding flashes of lightning in a night with no stars or 
street lights and the hours she hung onto her unconscious husband 
in a sea of debris 
the two suffering broken ribs and other injuries were rescued 
the next morning 
there are so many stories of horror from that storm said 
guice who has headed harrison countys emergency agency for 28 
years there was the apartment complex where at least 24 people 
drowned during a hurricane party and an episcopal church built in 
1849 where 13 members of one family died 
i keep thinking about the loss of life if only those people 
had responded to our evacuation call 
