using yellow legal pads 
the warning was intended to prepare local office workers for a 
sweeping new recycling law that goes into effect in the district of 
columbia on oct 1 and to discourage them from producing colored 
paper trash which many recycling firms dont want 
although yellow legal pads arent actually banned by the new law 
the order from joan rohlfs recycling coordinator for the 
metropolitan council of governments sent a chill through this town 
with the highest concentration of lawyers anywhere in the country 
more than 30000 of them or roughly one for every 22 residents 
does this portend the demise of the legal brief will there be 
fewer petitions to habeas the corpus will those friends of the 
court the amicus curiae be popping in less frequently to lend a 
helpful hand 
it means well have to use white legal pads i guess said 
michael horn a partner in the prestigious 240lawyer firm of 
covington amp burling 
yellow legal pads are suffering a decline in popularity among 
younger lawyers who prefer to use personal computers for their legal 
research and notekeeping horn said 
but us older fellows and gals are wedded to yellow legal pads 
im afraid he said my desk is littered with them right now 
arthur j rothkopf partner and chief spokesman for hogan amp 
hartson said the new law will mean headaches for landlords who 
must haul the trash away but not for lawyers 
well do things the way we always have rothkopf said 
therell always be yellow pads we lawyers cant live without 
them 
washington lawyer lawrence barcella a former assistant us 
attorney predicted that his colleagues will figure a way to pick 
at the law and get around it somehow possibly by using legal pads 
with a slightly different color such as beige or maybe mauve 
lawyers charge by the pound for paper whether its separated 
in piles for recycling or not barcella said theyll still 
figure out a way to make the law work for them 
the law signed by mayor marion barry in january is intended to 
help the district of columbia recycle more of the 720000 tons of 
trash it generates annually most of the citys solid wastes are 
burned in an incinerator or buried in a suburban virginia sanitary 
landfill that is expected to reach capacity in three years 
dc council member nadine p winter who sponsored the new law 
called washington a paper factory whose paper trash amounts to 
53 percent of the citys solid wastes compared with a national 
average of about 36 percent 
effective oct 1 according to ms rohlfs all paper trash 
newspapers magazines computer paper and office stationery must 
be collected separately for recycling keep the newspapers 
separate she said keep the computer paper separate keep out 
contaminants such as gum labels tape and seethrough envelopes and 
stop using yellow legal pads 
washington lawyer roslyn a mazer said crackdown on yellow legal 
pads might lead to a bright future for some of her colleagues 
many lawyers are frustrated gourmet ice cream salesmen 
baseball executives or proctologists she said the 
unavailability of the yellow legal pad will enable them to embark on 
fully satisfying careers 
</TEXT>
