<TEXT>
israeli authorities are depriving the 700000 
palestinians in the occupied gaza strip of adequate medical care as 
an additional means of battling the arab uprising a group of 
doctors alleged wednesday 
the israeli and palestinian doctors who wrote a report on 
medical conditions in the occupied lands said at a news conference 
that indifference by israeli authorities and political obstacles 
also have led to poor medical care in the territories 
the only psychiatric ward for gazans has no one trained in 
psychiatry and the only oncology department is run by a blood 
specialist rather than a cancer expert the doctors said in a report 
the group the association of israeli and palestinian physicians 
for human rights said that since the outbreak of the uprising a 
new tendency has appeared the use of medicine as an additional 
means of repression against the population 
the military governments chief medical officer in gaza denied 
the charges we dont mix medicine and politics said dr 
yitzhak peterburg 
he added that this physicians association is known for its 
imprecision and slanting of facts 
the doctors conceded that since israel captured the gaza strip 
from egypt in the 1967 middle east war medical treatment for gazans 
has vastly improved for example infant mortality has dropped from 
86 deaths per 1000 babies to 28 deaths between 1970 and 1988 
but they said the improvements came mainly because israeli 
hospitals were available to gaza residents they said facilities in 
gaza have been ignored 
the doctors said the need for medical care has risen steeply 
because of the 20monthold uprising which has killed 536 
palestinians and wounded thousands in clashes with the army and 
jewish settlers 
the inadequacy of medical services has created a situation where 
gazans are completely dependent on the decisions of the military 
government the doctors said 
it cited a severe shortage of doctors one per 1400 residents 
in gaza compared with one per 400 residents in israel it also 
claimed that israeli policies prevent dozens of arab doctors from 
working 
no services exist in gaza for chest or blood vessel surgery 
neurosurgery radiation treatment pathology or handicapped 
rehabilitation the report said 
it charged that during armyimposed curfews people who need 
medical care often could not get to clinics or hospitals it also 
said army troops had thrown tear gas inside hospitals and entered 
some facilities to beat patients and medical staff 
peterburg said soldiers were under strict orders not to interfere 
with hospitals but could enter to make arrests he said soldiers 
caught in beating incidents were punished 
while acknowledging that health services in gaza were not on a 
par with those of israel he said if you look at the area over a 
period of years and remember where we started the figures show that 
there has been constant improvement even during the uprising 
