<TEXT>
president mikhail s gorbachev and the kremlin 
leadership on wednesday rejected as unconstitutional a new estonian 
law that denies some russian residents of the balitic republic the 
right to vote 
they called it a violation of human rights 
however the supreme soviet presidium the governments top 
executive body has apparently sought to avoid a contest of wills 
with estonian leaders over the law which has touched off an 
8dayold protest strike by tens of thousands of ethnic russians who 
live in the tiny baltic republic 
instead the presidium said that by oct 1 estonias government 
would present the republics legislature with proposals to bring the 
law into line with the soviet constitution the tass news agency 
reported that seemed to indicate agreement on both sides to avert a 
crisis 
leaders in the republic of 16 million people which declared its 
sovereignty in november have rejected attempts by moscowbased 
authorities to annul their laws but both sides have avoided 
bringing matters to a head 
estonian president arnold ruutel met with the presidium in the 
kremlin wednesday and explained the reasons that led to adoption of 
the election law tass said it was not clear whether he agreed it 
should be revised 
ethnic estonians have called the morerestrictive law a necessity 
to ensure they maintain political control in their ethnic homeland 
and are not overwhelmed by an influx of ethnic russians and soviet 
outsiders lured by estonias higher living standards 
but the presidium found that the laws restrictions which 
justice minister veniamin yakovlev said constitute the soviet 
unions first residency requirements for voting and holding office 
violate human rights including in the international covenant on 
human rights tass said 
the law limits the right to vote and hold office to longterm 
residents 
among diplomatic commitments entered into by the soviets that are 
violated by the law is a covenent guarantee that each citizen 
should have the right and possibility to vote without any 
discrimination and without groundless restrictions the presidium 
said 
the soviet constitution its demands of equality of rights of 
citizens and equality of citizens before the law must be observed 
unconditionally there is no other way said vice president 
anatoly i lukyanov a gorbachev protege who chaired the meeting 
excerpts of the session were shown by state television 
gorbachev the presidiums chairman did not take part but tass 
said he signed the decree at the kremlin giving it his personal 
stamp of approval the soviet leader has been rumored to be on his 
customary august vacation 
the aug 8 decision of estonias supreme soviet parliament to 
limit the right of suffrage and officeholding ignited a strike that 
continued wednesday strike committee member vasily maximov said by 
