<TEXT>
dissident czechoslovak playwright vaclav 
havel urged his countrymen to refrain from street protests marking 
the 1968 sovietled invasion because such rallies may spur a harsh 
crackdown by authorities 
monday is the anniversary of the aug 21 1968 invasion that 
crushed the prague spring reforms that briefly liberalized czech 
society 
in a statement dated aug 14 and released wednesday by the 
londonbased emigre publishers palach press havel said he could 
understand that czechoslovaks might believe street protests are the 
only way to vent frustrations 
but he added i personally believe there is no point in 
resorting predominantly or exclusively to this method of protest now 
when authorities are waiting exactly for this type of action in 
order to be able to strike hard to paralyze peoples democratization 
for a long time to come 
havel instead urged citizens to sign the petition known as a 
few sentences which has garnered an estimated 15000 signatures 
since it was first distributed in late june 
the petition demands democratic reforms and negotiations with 
communist authorities it has come under fierce attack in the 
staterun media and from party leaders who have rejected the sort of 
political reforms occurring in poland hungary and the soviet union 
protests during last years anniversary failed to nudge the 
government closer to reform but resulted in at least three petitions 
for democratic change and an increased activism among dissidents 
this year authorities have warned they wont tolerate 
disturbances and will do what is necessary to maintain public order 
czechslovakias official human rights committee appealed to 
citizens to avert street violence on the anniversary prague 
newspapers reported wednesday 
the committee was established on dec 9 1988 in an apparent 
move to offset the rising wave of dissident protest but activists 
say it lacks the courage to speak out against police brutality 
having the experience of january we express our anxiety over 
the possible manifestations of demagoguery general nihilism or 
violence in the forthcoming days the human rights committees 
appeal warned 
the statement referred to protests that broke out in january 
marking the 20th anniversary of the death of jan palach who set 
himself on fire to protest the 1968 invasion 
havel was arrested during one such protest and was jailed for 
four months several dissidents have been harassed in advance of the 
anniversary dissidents jan carnogursky and miroslav kusy were 
