<TEXT>
the congressional budget office projects next 
years federal deficit at 141 billion well above the 110 billion 
target in the grammrudman balanced budget law figures obtained 
wednesday show 
the budget office which provides congress with nonpartisan 
fiscal information also estimates that without further action the 
shortfall will stay at about the same level through fiscal 1993 
the year grammrudman requires that the budget be brought into 
balance 
the new numbers reflect the recent enactment of the savings and 
loan bailout law and passage of the drought bill and another 
emergency spending measure 
the figures are of limited significance because the budget 
offices forecasts are not used in the grammrudman process 
instead it is the white houses office of management and budget 
perennially more optimistic than cbo whose projections are counted 
by the law 
in addition when congress returns from its august recess after 
labor day legislators will have nearly four weeks of work to find 
additional savings before the oct 1 start of fiscal 1990 among the 
measures lawmakers are already working on is one that would produce 
about 13 billion in savings from spending cuts and new tax receipts 
if grammrudman deficit ceilings are surpassed automatic 
spending reductions in defense and many domestic programs can be 
triggered 
but cbos figures which the agency officially releases thursday 
are noteworthy because they are respected by lawmakers and private 
economists who use them to measure the fiscal effects of programs 
and legislative proposals 
the executive branch plans to release its projections next week 
on capitol hill it is widely expected that omb will forecast a 116 
billion deficit for fiscal 1990 
the cbo projects a 161 billion deficit for this year up from 
155 billion in fiscal 1988 
the budget office is projecting that without any further action 
there would be deficits of 144 billion in fiscal 1991 141 billion 
in 1992 143 billion in 1993 and 128 billion in 1994 
the 1991 grammrudman deficit target is 64 billion 
congress enacted a 117 trillion budget blueprint for fiscal 
1990 last may cbo estimates that if all the savings contemplated in 
the budget were fully achieved next years deficit would be 118 
billion 
many of those savings however are not expected to be enacted 
for example conflicts between congress and the white house make a 
projected 57 billion in asset sales extremely unlikely 
the cbo estimates the savings and loan bailout legislation 
president bush signed into law last week would add 14 billion to 
this years deficit 4 billion to the 1990 shortfall and a total 
of 10 billion over the following four years 
ombs projections of the effect of the savings and loan bill are 
expected to be much different because the bailouts spending next 
year will not count on the budget omb is expected to claim a 
savings of about 125 billion resulting from the measures passage 
according to the republican staff of the senate budget committee 
