<TEXT>
as many as 1500 high school students involved in 
competition including athletes band members debaters and chess 
students could soon face drug tests under a proposal adopted by a 
suburban school board 
the proposal approved for homewoodflossmoor high by the district 
233 school board on tuesday night is believed to be one of the first 
involving all students in interscholastic competition only a 
handful of high schools across the country test athletes for drugs 
the feeling of the board is that these kids represent our 
school by wearing the uniform and carry our name in a different 
arena district 233 superintendent ed rachford said wednesday 
there was a firm belief that anyone representing the school has an 
obligation to be an example 
the proposal originated two months ago with football coach john 
wrenn who sought permission to test only those members of his team 
that he suspected might be using drugs 
i wanted to be able to reach the kids i felt had a problem but 
after all thats gone on i realize you cant play god and 
arbitrarily decide who you test wrenn said even so i didnt 
have the slightest idea it was going to wind up like this 
neither did the administration of the school in south suburban 
flossmoor the lone school in district 233 rachford concedes 
coach wrenn said he was willing to subject his program to this 
kind of scrutiny so the administration researched the legal 
questions and decided to expand it to include all athletes he 
said 
the board went even further amending the proposal to include all 
students involved in interscholastic activities the final package 
was approved by a 51 vote 
board member katherine cerone the lone dissenter said she 
wanted to hear more from parents teachers students and others in 
the community before approving the policy 
how the plan will be implemented remains to be worked out by the 
board but the details will be of great interest to school 
administrators elsewhere 
rachford however said he envisions many obstacles the school 
has 2100 students 1500 were in interscholastic activities last 
year 
we may be headed for legal challenges speaking practically 
who pays the public parents booster clubs merchants then in 
what order do we do this and how quickly can we afford to do it 
random testing or not 
there are a lot of questions to be answered before we bring 
this proposal back to the board on sept 5 when the 
administration will submit a detailed plan for final approval he 
said 
it sounds like we rushed into this rachford said but 
there was a lot of frustration that kids are endangering themselves 
and were unable to make a dent i think the idea is that any tool 
we can aquire would be an important step 
drug testing for high school athletes withstood its first legal 
challenge late last year when a federal appeals court ruled 
unanimously that a high school near lafayette ind could use 
randomly test athletes 
since then jake burton athletic director at john t mccutcheon 
high school said he has been deluged with inquiries from coaches 
