<DOCNO> AP890816-0220 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
industrial production rose a moderate 02 
percent in july but the factory operating rate remained flat the 
federal reserve board said today in a report that indicated further 
easing of inflationary pressures 
factory use held steady at 836 percent last month after 
declining 03 percentage point in june the central bank said the 
rate hit a 10year high of 843 percent last december last months 
operating rate was down from 837 percent a year earlier 
the closer us industry gets to full operating capacity the 
greater difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand leading 
to shortages and price increases analysts generally consider an 
operating rate of 85 percent or above as an indication of 
inflationary pressures 
the central bank has been straddling a fine line of keeping 
interest rates high enough to cool inflationary pressures without 
slowing growth so much that the economy slides into a recession it 
began letting rates drop in june as inflation seemed to lessen 
the federal reserve said its industrial production index in july 
stood at 1417 percent of its 1977 base up from 1414 percent in 
june 
the 02 percent increase last month came after revised 01 
percent drops in both may and june those were the first downturns 
since the index fell 02 percent in february which had been the 
first drop in a year 
but the fed said the july gain mainly reflected a rebound in the 
output of raw materials and continued strength in business equipment 
excluding autos 
in contract automoobile and truck production fell sharply and 
output of construction supplies on balance remained weak it 
said 
production at manufacturing plants making both durable and 
nondurable goods rose 02 percent output was up 03 percent at 
mines and oil wells and 08 percent at utilities 
the factory operating rate dipped 01 percentage point to 839 
percent at manufacturing plants down from junes revised 84 
percent the rate had peaked at 847 percent in january 
the rate at factories producing durable goods bigticket items 
expected to last more than three years fell 03 percentage point 
from 826 percent in june 
the rate at factories producing nondurable goods rose to 862 
percent from 861 percent in june 
</TEXT>
