a new agreement has been reached between the 
philippines and its creditor banks the second under the 
debtreduction proposals of treasury secretary nicholas f brady an 
international monetary source said today 
the source said the accord would both reduce the countrys 28 
billion debt and add new loans to it 
in last months agreement on the 108 billion debt of mexico a 
choice was given to creditor banks loan reductions interest 
reductions or new loans whether mexicos total debt will be larger 
or smaller remains to be worked out 
the source said the new agreement was reached in new york between 
representatives of the philippine government and a committee of 
banks led by manufacturers hanover trust co 
the source who spoke on condition of anonymity said the 
international monetary fund last may offered the philippines about 
206 million in loans that the government of president corazon 
aquino could use for debt relief in the present state of the 
market the government can settle old loans for about 50 cents on 
the dollar 
the washington post which first reported the debt agreement 
cited treasury officials and bankers saying they dont consider the 
accord a break with the brady plan because it envisions that the 
philippines will try to reduce its indebtedness 
additional money for debt relief is expected from the world bank 
the funds sister organization in washington 
the money could also be used to reduce interest rates on the old 
loans the burden of interest payments is the heaviest part of the 
third worlds 13 trillion debt 
