negotiators representing the philippines and 
the countrys major bank creditors today announced a tentative 
agreement on a package of debt reduction the second pact to be 
reached under the bush administrations to new initiative 
philippine central bank governor jose b fernandez jr who led 
his countrys negotiating team said the tentative deal met the 
guidelines established by us treasury secretary nicholas brady in 
march 
there is no question that we must reduce the countrys existing 
stock of commercial bank debt if we are to sustain the countrys 
economic growth he said at the same time new commerical bank 
financing is critical for our program as the combined effect of our 
debt reduction initiatives and our improving economy work to bring 
about the end of the debt problem for the philippines 
officials said the new accord would reduce the philippines 28 
billion debt and also provide new loans the two elements the 
countrys negotiators had considered critical to keeping the 
philippine economy expanding 
the new debt package was the second agreement achieved under the 
brady debt plan which is seeking to get commercial banks to forgive 
a portion of their third world loans in exchange for guarantees of 
repayment of the remaining debt 
last month mexico the developing worlds second largest debtor 
with 108 billion owed reach an accord following the brady plans 
guidelines 
in the mexican agreement creditor banks were given a choice of 
loan reductions interest reductions or providing new money 
