<DOCNO> AP890816-0231 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
bell communications research said wednesday it 
has developed a prototype version of an inexpensive sensor for leaks 
from underground fuel tanks 
leaking fuel can contaminate wells and reservoirs and the 
environmental protection agency recently required that all 
underground fuel storage tanks be monitored for leaks by the end of 
1993 
bellcore said its sensor is made of a material that stops 
conducting electricity when it absorbs fuel when the electricity 
shuts off an alarm is triggered above ground 
bellcore based in livingston nj is the research arm of the 
seven regional bell telephone companies as well as cincinnati bell 
and southern new england telephone it developed the sensor for 
manholes because fuel leaking into them can endanger workers and 
damage cables 
the epa estimates there are leaks in more than 10 percent of the 
3 million to 5 million underground storage tanks for gasoline 
kerosene fuel oil and other hydrocarbon fuels across the country 
bellcore said it has applied for a patent and plans to license 
the technology by the end of the year to other companies including 
ones that could manufacture the sensors 
</TEXT>
