housing starts driven down for four months by 
high mortgage rates rose for the second straight month in july the 
government reported wednesday and analysts said singlefamily 
construction should continue at a moderate pace the rest of the year 
the interest rate drops in june definitely have begun to hit 
the market said john a tuccillo chief economist for the 
national association of realtors who predicted further interest 
rate declines will keep housing activity strong in the months ahead 
the consumer is coming off the sidelines as mortgage rates 
fall commented thomas holloway senior economist for the mortgage 
bankers association of america 
the commerce department said housing starts were up 08 percent 
last month following an 85 percent hike in june new homes and 
apartments were started in july at a seasonally adjusted annual rate 
of 143 million up from 142 million in june 
starts had fallen for four consecutive months through may as the 
federal reserve drove up interest rates to slow the economy and curb 
inflation that was the longest string of declines since housing 
activity slowed for five months in februaryjune 1987 
but as economic growth moderated the fed began nudging rates 
downward fixedrate 30year mortgages fell from 1122 percent in 
march to 996 percent last friday according to a survey by the 
federal home loan mortgage corp 
despite the overall rebound analysts saw problems in the 
multifamily component of the housing starts report 
while the singlefamily sector posted a 63 percent increase to 
104 million units annually in july apartment starts were off 12 
percent to 389000 units 
part of the decline in apartment starts was attributed to a heady 
329 percent increase in june which chief economist david berson of 
the federal national mortgage association said was unsustainable 
in view of the high vacancy rates 
michael carliner an economist at the national association of 
home builders said high rents and the elimination of tax incentives 
by the 1986 tax reform added to the weak multifamily pace 
and housing economist michael sumichrast said the 154 percent 
drop in apartment buildingpermit applications tells me that 
starts are going to decline sharply in the fall building permits 
are seen as a barometer of future multifamily housing activity 
singlefamily starts had risen 02 percent in june after falling 
51 percent in may and 47 percent in april apartment starts had 
increased 54 percent in may after falling 266 percent in april 
the northeast paced overall housing construction with a 16 
