<TEXT>
she got caught in a blizzard in the sierra nevada 
mountains while searching for a rugged outdoorswoman for mjb coffee 
commercials 
she toured the new york sewer system sang offkey for strangers 
in portland ore and prowled the docks before dawn at newport 
ri all in pursuit of average folks for television commercials 
kathy s sorkin 41 is founder and president of faces and places 
inc a new yorkbased casting agency that finds real people for 
advertising 
that task often requires the resourcefulness of a detective the 
perseverance of an athlete and a talent for setting strangers at 
ease twenty people on average are interviewed for every one that 
winds up in an ad 
its a lot of work doing that said daisy sinclair head of 
casting for the advertising agency ogilvy amp mather there is a 
special talent to stopping people cold and getting them to talk 
ms sorkin said the key is in being a good listener 
you have to listen for that clue to what they are hiding she 
said a man comes in saying i dont know what you are interested 
in me for to get that person talking and animated is a real 
challenge to me 
ms sorkin said using such characters adds credibility to the 
sales pitch because there is a genuine quality to real people that 
actors cant give you 
she wouldnt discuss what she charges clients for the farflung 
talent hunts but said the work keeps her on the road most of the 
year 
even when shes back in new york ms sorkin said shes never 
really off the job take her assignment from the new york state 
lottery for instance 
lottery officials trying to refute criticism that the game preys 
on poor people wanted advertising that demonstrated it appeals to 
rich people too 
ms sorkin staked out wall street and highbrow stores like 
bloomingdales and came up with dozens of people who got to dream 
aloud about what they would do with the money if they were to win 
the lottery 
but walking home one night she found a uniformed doorman who 
wound up in one ad saying that since his father liked to fish hed 
buy him a lake 
asked to find an authority on the perennial alligators in the 
sewers rumors for an ad about a new york radio station ms sorkin 
interviewed sewer workers and said they insisted on showing her 
their slimy abode no alligators showed up 
but most of her work takes her outside new york 
she went to portland ore for instance in search of people who 
would sing a jingle for kit kat candy bars she crooned for some 
candidates to set them at ease and see if they could hold a tune 
her search for the mjb coffee woman took her through a blizzard 
in the mountain passes in northern california before she found the 
right one near grass valley calif 
for a swansons fried chicken dinner commercial ms sorkin and 
her assistants fanned out from san francisco to sacramento 
searching the parks supermarkets financial districts restaurants 
and movie waiting lines 
she spent days on the docks before dawn in newport ri seeking 
fishermen heading to sea who used alka seltzer plus for tough colds 
the swanson and alka seltzer ads featured people saying why they 
use a specific brand the socalled testimonial approach requires 
special precautions 
to protect the credibility of the people chosen for such ads ms 
sorkin makes sure candidates never suspect they are under 
consideration for starring in a commercial 
she and her assistants describing themselves as market 
researchers often stop people by asking if they would like to 
participate in a consumer survey 
the questions are designed to determine if interviewees use a 
specific brand that will be advertised without letting them know 
what the product is or that the admakers are seeking people for a 
commercial 
those who qualify are invited to another questionandanswer 
session which is videotaped the tape serves as the legal record 
that they volunteered they use a specific brand 
television networks which try to guard against deceptive 
advertising often demand proof that interviewees werent coached 
as an added safeguard against deception ms sorkin said many 
people arent told until after the ad has been shot that they were 
filmed for a commercial and will be paid for it those who dont 
want to participate are dropped 
pay varies depending on the role ms sorkin said people in a 
principal role usually get a onetime fee and extra payments based 
on how often and how widely the ad runs 
faces and places goes to extraordinary lengths to find credible 
people but it isnt the only agency specializing in seeking 
nonprofessionals for commercial roles 
laura slutsky for instance has run the new yorkbased 
peoplefinders agency for 15 years among her recent finds have been 
several families for surf detergent commercials and autoworkers who 
describe the pride they feel in their jobs in a ford motor co ad 
campaign 
she also worked on alka seltzer plus commercials persuading 30 
montana ranchers to travel up to 100 miles in the dead of winter to 
discuss their colds with her on videotape at a helena hotel eight 
of them made the commercial 
but sometimes hard work doesnt pay off 
ms sorkin said she interviewed 300 people a day for a week in 
bristol tenn for a slice soft drink commercial but couldnt find 
people who pronounced the drinks name without a southern lilt she 
said the admaker eventually flew in outsiders to appear in the ads 
its an exhausting process said michael leonard senior vice 
president at hal riney amp partners a san franciscobased ad agency 
that worked with ms sorkin on the mjb coffee and swansons dinner 
ads 
ms sorkin said she figures her work is helping people partly 
fulfill artist andy warhols prophecy that everyone will be famous 
for 15 minutes she helps them get there for about 30 seconds 
</TEXT>
